                <head>267. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>Contacts between the United States and the National Liberation Front (<gloss
                        target="#t_NLF1">NLF</gloss>) regarding military issues occurred at the end
                    of 1968. On December 19 the <gloss target="#t_NLF1">NLF</gloss> offered to
                    release three American prisoners of war. Following meetings on December 25,
                    1968, and January 1, 1969, between <gloss target="#t_VietCongVietcong1">Viet
                        Cong</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> military officers in an
                    area of Tay Ninh Province where a temporary stand-down had been ordered, the
                    three soldiers were released. Seven North Vietnamese seamen were subsequently
                    released by the <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> Navy on December 16. Despite
                    this successful “exchange,” the <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> and South
                    Vietnamese Governments refused to recognize a <gloss
                        target="#t_VietCongVietcong1">Viet Cong</gloss>-sponsored New Year’s truce
                    due to enemy violations of an earlier Christmas truce. Documentation on the
                    prisoner release is in the <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName>
                    Library, National Security File, Country File, Vietnam, 3 D (1), Prisoners of
                    War (General Material), 1/66-1/69; and in National Archives and Records
                    Administration, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1967-69,
                        <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 17-5 <gloss target="#t_US1"
                        >US</gloss>-<gloss target="#t_VIET1">VIET</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_S1">S</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 27-7
                        <gloss target="#t_VIET1">VIET</gloss>.</p>
